The paper discusses the quantification of resources needed for computations, which is a fundamental topic in computer science. The use of Computability Logic and the application to cryptanalysis and neural nets suggest that cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) are likely sub-categories. The discussion of information storage and computational trade-offs suggests cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) as possible sub-categories. Finally, the application to cryptanalysis suggests cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) as a possible sub-category.
